## 3. How an OCaml user will consume the API

```ocaml
open Pcapng

let () =
  let cap = open_file "capture.pcapng" in
  (* Example: count all packets whose length > 1500 bytes *)
  let cnt = ref 0 in
  let cb frame =
    if Bytes.length frame.data > 1500 then incr cnt
  in
  iter_frames cap cb;
  Printf.printf "Large packets: %d\n%!" !cnt;
  close cap
```

The heavy work (`Iterator::next`) stays in C++ and the only OCaml work per
frame is the allocation of a small record and the execution of `cb`.  The
runtime lock is held only while the callback runs, so the iteration can run
concurrently with other OCaml threads (e.g. a UI thread) without starving
them.

--- 

**That’s it!**  
You now have a minimal, high‑performance binding that lets OCaml code walk a
C++ iterator of 800 million frames while keeping the hot loop in native code
and preserving correct interaction with the OCaml garbage collector and
exception mechanism. Adjust the `#include` and iterator‑type names to match
the exact libpcapng API you are using.
